se in an urban high school to make the case for critical hip-hop pedagogies. Pairing rap music with its less controversial cousins, spoken word and slam poetry, this course honored and extended student interests. It also confronted the barriers of race, class, gender, and generation that can separate white teachers from classrooms of predominantly black and Latino students and students from each other. Bronwen Low builds a surprising argument: the very reasons teachers might resist the introduction of hip-hop into the planned curriculum are what make hip-hop so pedagogically vital. Class discussions on topics such as what one can and cannot say in the school auditorium or who can use the N-word raised pressing and difficult questions about language, culture and identity. As she reveals, an innovative, student-centered pedagogy based on spoken word curriculum that is willing to tolerate conflict, as well as ambivalence, has the potential to air tensions and lead to new insights and understandings for both teachers and students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCritical pedagogyzUnited States. 0aEducation, SecondaryxCurriculazUnited States. 0aEducational anthropologyzUnited States. 0aHip-hopzUnited StatesxInfluence. 0aIntergroup relationszUnited States. 0aLanguage arts (Secondary)xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMulticultural educationzUnited States. 0aPerformance poetryxStudy and teaching (Secondary)zUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477753740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804777537423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804777537.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alle